CHAT.comment: Ross has two ways of making plurals: 1. to make them end in consonant s , and that works after almost every consonant that he can make it end after , where it will sound and you can here the difference between the s and the consonant , 2.to make them in sibilants iz or es , which will work for churches , glasses , and which ends up producing things like cowses , freezes. The only exceptions are a few well-learned forms like keys , but he doesn't even know cows very well. The last thing that he is learning is that you just need a z after a vowel. He hasn't heard very many of those .

In the past tense Ross does very nice on his affix checking . He seems to regularly accepts words that end in a "t" particularly , and a "d" somewhat less , as already being past tense , and doesn't continue to mark them. That extends even to something like "fight" which you you think he might know the past tense of , like "fought" but he doesn't , but he really likes "they fight" as if it were the past tense , and that's the past tense he gives. There are a few past tenses that he doesn't want to say at all , like "ate"
